. A qualified local estate agent can help you find suitable homes and negotiate with sellers. At this stage, you should also start consulting a property lawyer or solicitor to advise you from the outset. While not legally mandatory to have a lawyer, it is highly advisable to hire an independent conveyancing lawyer who represents only your interestsâ€‹
LEGALIASPAIN.COM
.
Viewing and Making an Offer: Visit the property (or have a representative view it) and decide if it meets your needs. When you find the right property, you will make a formal offer, usually through the estate agent. If the offer is accepted, itâ€™s common to sign a preliminary reservation contract and pay a small holding deposit (often around a few thousand euros) to reserve the propertyâ€‹
CDSOLICITORS.COM
. The agent will then mark the property as reserved. This reservation document should be signed by the agent and acknowledges receipt of your depositâ€‹
LEGALIASPAIN.COM
. Importantly, this initial deposit is typically refundable if you decide not to proceed, as the reservation agreement binds the agent but not yet the buyerâ€‹
LEGALIASPAIN.COM
.
Hire a Lawyer and Obtain an NIE: As early as possible, engage your independent Spanish property lawyer (if you havenâ€™t already) to start the legal process. One of the first legal requirements is obtaining an NIE (NÃºmero de IdentificaciÃ³n de Extranjero), which is a foreign buyerâ€™s tax identification number. An NIE is required for any fiscal transaction in Spain, including opening a bank account or buying propertyâ€‹
GOV.UK
. You can apply for an NIE through a Spanish consulate in your home country or in Spain (often via the immigration office or designated police station)â€‹
GOV.UK
. Your lawyer can also obtain your NIE on your behalf via Power of Attorney if you cannot be presentâ€‹
CDSOLICITORS.COM
. At this stage, you should also open a Spanish bank account to facilitate payments for the purchase and future bills. The bank will ask for proof of funds origin due to anti-money laundering rules, so be prepared with documentationâ€‹
LEGALIASPAIN.COM
.
Due Diligence and Legal Checks: Before signing any purchase contract, your conveyancing lawyer will perform thorough due diligence on the property. This includes verifying the sellerâ€™s title and that the propertyâ€™s details match the Land Registry records, checking for any debts, liens or mortgages on the property, and ensuring all planning permissions and building licenses are in orderâ€‹
