. Itâ€™s crucial to confirm there are no outstanding debts (such as unpaid taxes, community fees, or utilities), because in Spain, certain debts attached to the property (notably utilities or community fees) can become the responsibility of the new owner if not clearedâ€‹
CDSOLICITORS.COM
. You or your lawyer should obtain a Land Registry extract (nota simple) to review the registered status of the property â€“ confirming ownership and encumbrancesâ€‹
GOV.UK
. If the property is part of a building or community, also review the community bylaws and latest fee payments. Any legal irregularities or issues uncovered now should be resolved or reflected in the contract. Itâ€™s advisable not to sign a binding contract or pay a large deposit until due diligence is satisfactorily completed.
Private Purchase Contract (Contrato de Arras) and Deposit: Once due diligence is done (or adequate protections are in place if itâ€™s still in progressâ€‹
